    {
      "id": "CTOvz1Ge7yodw39V-eP9N",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 299.4581603235828,
      "y": 7048.343978759467,
      "width": 404.2568359375,
      "height": 140,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "c0d9",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 949090027,
      "version": 496,
      "versionNonce": 1197487658,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1783161346429,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1. Know what is ERC- 4626 \n2. Use Hardhat & Foundry \n3. Deploy a contract & a useful one with real logic \n    integrate that with frontend & backend \n4. Write API routes (backend) for the same \n5. Works with attacks & risk with smart contracts \n ",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. Know what is ERC- 4626 \n2. Use Hardhat & Foundry \n3. Deploy a contract & a useful one with real logic \n    integrate that with frontend & backend \n4. Write API routes (backend) for the same \n5. Works with attacks & risk with smart contracts \n ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "x56YYXIELjqXJ0QNZsnpG",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1012.3896653318179,
      "y": 6816.77252262417,
      "width": 620.417236328125,
      "height": 540,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "c0dA",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 367113189,
      "version": 2510,
      "versionNonce": 109386102,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1783161346429,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1. Lets keep things simple here :  \n    token : what is it? \n    \nA token can represent virtually anything in Eth by anything I mean \nliterally anything, it can : \n\n> represent goals scored by Messi in a world-cup match\n> represent grand slam title Novak Djokovic holds\n> represent no of world cups won by Australia \n\nso according to Etherum protocol, this very powerful feature needs \na standard, here comes ERC-20. It allows devs to build application \naround tokens by building I am guessing it has some API's & not only \nthat but docs also mention these apps are interoperable with products\n& services so my hunch is they mean that these tokens they can actually \ndisplay what they represent on multiple platforms, this is what they mean \nfrom interoperable from products & services is what I am guessing  \n\nDoubt has been cleared on all points: \n1. On it allows devs: meaning for a token to be recognized as a token\nthere are same functions that must be implemented by the contract user \nis writing to be recognized as an ERC-20 token \n\n2. Interoperable: meaning an app knows ERC-20 Standard they can interact \nwith my custom token without any extra piece of code, because every ERC-20 \ntoken implements the same function the same way, so its like a guarantee or a \nsort of agreement they reach to    ",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. Lets keep things simple here :  \n    token : what is it? \n    \nA token can represent virtually anything in Eth by anything I mean \nliterally anything, it can : \n\n> represent goals scored by Messi in a world-cup match\n> represent grand slam title Novak Djokovic holds\n> represent no of world cups won by Australia \n\nso according to Etherum protocol, this very powerful feature needs \na standard, here comes ERC-20. It allows devs to build application \naround tokens by building I am guessing it has some API's & not only \nthat but docs also mention these apps are interoperable with products\n& services so my hunch is they mean that these tokens they can actually \ndisplay what they represent on multiple platforms, this is what they mean \nfrom interoperable from products & services is what I am guessing  \n\nDoubt has been cleared on all points: \n1. On it allows devs: meaning for a token to be recognized as a token\nthere are same functions that must be implemented by the contract user \nis writing to be recognized as an ERC-20 token \n\n2. Interoperable: meaning an app knows ERC-20 Standard they can interact \nwith my custom token without any extra piece of code, because every ERC-20 \ntoken implements the same function the same way, so its like a guarantee or a \nsort of agreement they reach to    ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "CLO_l7VpSieGu3WOXZ2LW",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1964.3340441400767,
      "y": 6830.527539423149,
      "width": 796.83349609375,
      "height": 60,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "c0dB",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 593586901,
      "version": 542,
      "versionNonce": 1661722858,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1783161346429,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "2. This is something I haven't understood: \nhow can tokens be similar, like my earlier example tokens representing Messi's goals & Djokovic's slams \nthey both are different values altogether, so how come docs say each token is same (value & type)  ",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "2. This is something I haven't understood: \nhow can tokens be similar, like my earlier example tokens representing Messi's goals & Djokovic's slams \nthey both are different values altogether, so how come docs say each token is same (value & type)  ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
